<!--
	ws-surface-integrals.ptx
	Section 3 (Surface Integrals, Stokes', and the Divergence Theorem),
	worksheet 12: Parametrized Surfaces and Surface Integrals.

	Ported from the Beamer deck 03_01_SurfaceIntegrals.tex (in
	outdated-material/notes/, surface-integrals folder): parametrizing a
	surface r(u,v), the tangent vectors r_u and r_v, the normal
	N = r_u x r_v, surface area, and the flux integral. Book concepts
	tracked from sec_parametric_surfaces / sec_surface_area /
	sec_surface_integral. Example equations are NOT reused from the deck
	or the book.

	This OPENS Section 3. The flux integral here is the object that Stokes'
	Theorem and the Divergence Theorem will act on in the next two
	worksheets.

	Authored to the SHARED worksheet conventions
	(checklists/worksheet-conventions.md): paired component="stu"/"key"
	reading checks and exercises; one True/False misconception check; one
	read-along TikZ figure; one modern application. Standard notation
	(macros from source/notes/bookends/docinfo.ptx); no new macros. The
	non-unit normal is written \mathbf{N} (no \vN macro); the unit normal
	uses the existing \vn. Math-valued answer keys are underlined directly
	(\underline{...}); only plain-word answers are bolded, so the pdf-key
	(LaTeX) build stays clean.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-surface-integrals">
	<title>Parametrized Surfaces and Surface Integrals</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>Parametrize a surface as <m>\vr(u,v) = [\,x(u,v),\,y(u,v),\,z(u,v)\,]</m>.</li>
			<li>Compute the tangent vectors <m>\vr_u</m>, <m>\vr_v</m> and the normal <m>\mathbf{N} = \vr_u \times \vr_v</m>.</li>
			<li>Compute surface area as <m>\iint_R \norm{\vr_u \times \vr_v}\,du\,dv</m>.</li>
			<li>Compute the <term>flux</term> of a field, <m>\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iint_R \vF(\vr(u,v))\cdot\mathbf{N}\,du\,dv</m>.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: Parametrizing a surface; tangents and normal
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>I. A surface takes two parameters.</term></p>

		<p>
			A curve needed one parameter; a <term>surface</term> needs two.
			We describe <m>S</m> by <m>\vr(u,v) = [\,x(u,v),\,y(u,v),\,z(u,v)\,]</m>.
			Holding one parameter fixed and varying the other traces a curve
			on <m>S</m>, so the partial derivatives
			<md>
				\vr_u = [\,x_u,\,y_u,\,z_u\,], \qquad
				\vr_v = [\,x_v,\,y_v,\,z_v\,]
			</md>
			are tangent to the surface. Their cross product is normal (perpendicular) to
			<m>S</m>:
			<md>
				\mathbf{N} = \vr_u \times \vr_v ,
				\qquad \vn = \frac{\mathbf{N}}{\norm{\mathbf{N}}} .
			</md>
			A surface given as a graph <m>z = f(x,y)</m> is parametrized
			simply by <m>\vr(u,v) = [\,u,\,v,\,f(u,v)\,]</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="ws-surfint-fig-normal">
			<caption>A surface patch with tangent vectors <m>\vr_u</m>,
				<m>\vr_v</m> and the normal <m>\mathbf{N} = \vr_u\times\vr_v</m>
				standing perpendicular to it.</caption>
			<image width="48%">
				<shortdescription>A skewed parallelogram representing a patch of a surface, with two tangent-vector arrows along its edges from one corner and a third arrow rising perpendicular to the patch, labeled as the normal vector.</shortdescription>
				<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.05,>=stealth]
	\coordinate (O) at (0,0);
	\coordinate (U) at (2.6,0.5);
	\coordinate (V) at (0.7,1.5);
	\coordinate (W) at (3.3,2.0);
	\fill[blue!8] (O)--(U)--(W)--(V)--cycle;
	\draw[blue!55] (O)--(U)--(W)--(V)--cycle;
	\node[blue!55] at (1.75,1.05) {$S$};
	% tangent vectors
	\draw[very thick, red, ->] (O) -- (U);
	\node[red, anchor=north] at (2.55,0.45) {$\vr_u$};
	\draw[very thick, teal, ->] (O) -- (V);
	\node[teal, anchor=east] at (0.62,1.5) {$\vr_v$};
	% normal
	\draw[very thick, ->] (O) -- (0.55,2.35);
	\node[anchor=south] at (0.6,2.35) {$\mathbf{N}=\vr_u\times\vr_v$};
	\fill (O) circle (1.6pt);
	\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<!-- reading-check pair 1 -->
		<p component="stu">
			A surface is described by <m>\vr(u,v)</m> with
			<fillin characters="3"/> <nbsp/>parameters. The vectors
			<m>\vr_u</m> and <m>\vr_v</m> are <fillin characters="8"/>
			<nbsp/>to the surface, and their cross product
			<m>\mathbf{N} = </m> <fillin characters="8"/> is normal to it.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			A surface is described by <m>\vr(u,v)</m> with
			<m>\underline{\textbf{two}}</m> parameters. The vectors
			<m>\vr_u</m> and <m>\vr_v</m> are
			<m>\underline{\textbf{tangent}}</m> to the surface, and their
			cross product
			<m>\mathbf{N} = \underline{\vr_u \times \vr_v}</m> is normal to
			it.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Parametrize the graph surface <m>z = x + y^2</m> and find
					the normal vector <m>\mathbf{N} = \vr_u \times \vr_v</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Parametrize the graph surface <m>z = x + y^2</m> and find
					the normal vector <m>\mathbf{N} = \vr_u \times \vr_v</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					As a graph, <m>\vr(u,v) = [\,u,\; v,\; u + v^2\,]</m>. Then
					<m>\vr_u = [\,1,\,0,\,1\,]</m> and
					<m>\vr_v = [\,0,\,1,\,2v\,]</m>, so
					<md>
						\mathbf{N} = \vr_u \times \vr_v
						= [\,(0)(2v) - (1)(1),\;\; (1)(0) - (1)(2v),\;\; (1)(1) - (0)(0)\,]
						= [\,-1,\; -2v,\; 1\,] .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Parametrize the graph surface <m>z = x^2 - y</m> and find
					<m>\mathbf{N} = \vr_u \times \vr_v</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Parametrize the graph surface <m>z = x^2 - y</m> and find
					<m>\mathbf{N} = \vr_u \times \vr_v</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Here <m>\vr(u,v) = [\,u,\; v,\; u^2 - v\,]</m>, so
					<m>\vr_u = [\,1,\,0,\,2u\,]</m> and
					<m>\vr_v = [\,0,\,1,\,-1\,]</m>. Then
					<md>
						\mathbf{N} = \vr_u \times \vr_v
						= [\,(0)(-1) - (2u)(1),\;\; (2u)(0) - (1)(-1),\;\; (1)(1) - (0)(0)\,]
						= [\,-2u,\; 1,\; 1\,] .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: Surface area
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>II. Surface area.</term></p>

		<p>
			A small patch of <m>S</m> is nearly the parallelogram spanned by
			<m>\vr_u\,du</m> and <m>\vr_v\,dv</m>, whose area is
			<m>\norm{\vr_u \times \vr_v}\,du\,dv</m>. Adding up these patches
			over the parameter region <m>R</m> gives the
			<term>surface area</term>:
			<md>
				\text{Area}(S) = \iint_S dS
				= \iint_R \norm{\vr_u \times \vr_v}\,du\,dv .
			</md>
			The length of the normal is the local area-scaling factor.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 2 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The surface-area element is <m>dS = </m> <fillin characters="10"/>
			<m>\,du\,dv</m>, the area of the little parallelogram spanned by
			<m>\vr_u\,du</m> and <m>\vr_v\,dv</m>. Surface area is a
			<fillin characters="6"/> <nbsp/>quantity.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The surface-area element is
			<m>dS = \underline{\norm{\vr_u \times \vr_v}}\,du\,dv</m>, the area
			of the little parallelogram spanned by <m>\vr_u\,du</m> and
			<m>\vr_v\,dv</m>. Surface area is a
			<m>\underline{\textbf{scalar}}</m> quantity.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the lateral surface area of the cylinder
					<m>\vr(u,v) = [\,3\cos u,\; 3\sin u,\; v\,]</m>, for
					<m>0\le u\le 2\pi</m> and <m>0\le v\le 5</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the lateral surface area of the cylinder
					<m>\vr(u,v) = [\,3\cos u,\; 3\sin u,\; v\,]</m>, for
					<m>0\le u\le 2\pi</m> and <m>0\le v\le 5</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Here <m>\vr_u = [\,-3\sin u,\; 3\cos u,\; 0\,]</m> and
					<m>\vr_v = [\,0,\,0,\,1\,]</m>, so
					<md>
						\mathbf{N} = \vr_u \times \vr_v
						= [\,3\cos u,\; 3\sin u,\; 0\,],
						\qquad
						\norm{\mathbf{N}} = \sqrt{9\cos^2 u + 9\sin^2 u} = 3 .
					</md>
					Therefore
					<md>
						\text{Area}(S) = \int_0^{5}\!\!\int_0^{2\pi} 3\,du\,dv
						= 3(2\pi)(5) = 30\pi ,
					</md>
					matching the lateral area <m>2\pi r h = 2\pi(3)(5) = 30\pi</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the area of the piece of the plane
					<m>z = 2x + y</m> lying above the unit square
					<m>0\le x\le 1</m>, <m>0\le y\le 1</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the area of the piece of the plane
					<m>z = 2x + y</m> lying above the unit square
					<m>0\le x\le 1</m>, <m>0\le y\le 1</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Parametrize as <m>\vr(u,v) = [\,u,\; v,\; 2u + v\,]</m>, so
					<m>\vr_u = [\,1,\,0,\,2\,]</m>,
					<m>\vr_v = [\,0,\,1,\,1\,]</m>, and
					<m>\mathbf{N} = [\,-2,\,-1,\,1\,]</m> with
					<m>\norm{\mathbf{N}} = \sqrt{4+1+1} = \sqrt{6}</m>. Since the
					square has area <m>1</m>,
					<md>
						\text{Area}(S) = \int_0^1\!\!\int_0^1 \sqrt{6}\,du\,dv
						= \sqrt{6} .
					</md>
					The slanted plane has <m>\sqrt6</m> times the area of its
					shadow.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: Flux
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>III. Flux through a surface.</term></p>

		<p>
			The <term>flux</term> of a vector field <m>\vF</m> through
			<m>S</m> measures how much of <m>\vF</m> passes through the
			surface. Dotting <m>\vF</m> with the unit normal and integrating,
			then using <m>\vn\,dS = \mathbf{N}\,du\,dv</m>, gives a formula
			with no square roots:
			<md>
				\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS
				= \iint_R \vF(\vr(u,v))\cdot\mathbf{N}\,du\,dv,
				\qquad \mathbf{N} = \vr_u \times \vr_v .
			</md>
			If <m>\vF = \rho\,\vv</m> is a fluid of density <m>\rho</m> moving
			with velocity <m>\vv</m>, the flux is the rate at which mass
			crosses <m>S</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 3 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The flux of <m>\vF</m> through <m>S</m> is
			<m>\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iint_R \vF(\vr(u,v))\cdot</m>
			<fillin characters="4"/> <m>\,du\,dv</m>. Flux measures how much of
			the field passes <fillin characters="8"/> <nbsp/>the surface.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The flux of <m>\vF</m> through <m>S</m> is
			<m>\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iint_R \vF(\vr(u,v))\cdot
			\underline{\mathbf{N}}\,du\,dv</m>. Flux measures how much of the
			field passes <m>\underline{\textbf{through}}</m> the surface.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="3in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Compute the flux of <m>\vF = [\,x,\,y,\,z\,]</m> outward
					through the cylinder
					<m>\vr(u,v) = [\,3\cos u,\; 3\sin u,\; v\,]</m> from page 2
					(<m>0\le u\le 2\pi</m>, <m>0\le v\le 5</m>).
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Compute the flux of <m>\vF = [\,x,\,y,\,z\,]</m> outward
					through the cylinder
					<m>\vr(u,v) = [\,3\cos u,\; 3\sin u,\; v\,]</m> from page 2
					(<m>0\le u\le 2\pi</m>, <m>0\le v\le 5</m>).
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					From page 2, <m>\mathbf{N} = [\,3\cos u,\; 3\sin u,\; 0\,]</m>
					(pointing radially outward). Along the surface
					<m>\vF = [\,x,\,y,\,z\,] = [\,3\cos u,\; 3\sin u,\; v\,]</m>,
					so
					<md>
						\vF\cdot\mathbf{N}
						= 9\cos^2 u + 9\sin^2 u + 0 = 9 .
					</md>
					Therefore
					<md>
						\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS
						= \int_0^{5}\!\!\int_0^{2\pi} 9\,du\,dv
						= 9(2\pi)(5) = 90\pi .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Compute the flux of <m>\vF = [\,0,\,0,\,z\,]</m> upward
					through the plane piece <m>\vr(u,v) = [\,u,\,v,\,2u+v\,]</m>
					over the unit square (<m>0\le u\le 1</m>,
					<m>0\le v\le 1</m>) from page 2.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Compute the flux of <m>\vF = [\,0,\,0,\,z\,]</m> upward
					through the plane piece <m>\vr(u,v) = [\,u,\,v,\,2u+v\,]</m>
					over the unit square (<m>0\le u\le 1</m>,
					<m>0\le v\le 1</m>) from page 2.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Here <m>\mathbf{N} = [\,-2,\,-1,\,1\,]</m> and along the
					surface <m>\vF = [\,0,\,0,\,z\,] = [\,0,\,0,\,2u+v\,]</m>, so
					<m>\vF\cdot\mathbf{N} = 2u + v</m>. Then
					<md>
						\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS
						= \int_0^1\!\!\int_0^1 (2u + v)\,du\,dv
						= \int_0^1 (1 + v)\,dv = \tfrac32 .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: A misconception, an application, and looking ahead
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>IV. A caution and an application.</term></p>

		<!-- misconception check: single exercise, solution instructor-only -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-surfint-tf-orientation">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<alert>True or False.</alert> Using
					<m>\vr_v \times \vr_u</m> in place of
					<m>\vr_u \times \vr_v</m> gives the same flux through
					<m>S</m>. Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					<term>False.</term> The cross product is anti-commutative:
					<m>\vr_v \times \vr_u = -(\vr_u \times \vr_v)</m>, so
					swapping the order reverses the normal and therefore
					<em>flips the sign</em> of the flux. A surface must be
					<term>oriented</term> <ndash/> we must choose which way the
					normal points (for a closed surface, conventionally
					outward) <ndash/> and every flux value is stated relative
					to that choice.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>An application.</term></p>

		<!-- application (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Air moves straight up a circular ventilation duct with
					velocity <m>\vv = [\,0,\,0,\,3\,]</m> m/s. Model the duct's
					cross-section as the flat disk <m>S</m> of radius <m>2</m> m
					in a horizontal plane, with upward unit normal
					<m>\vn = [\,0,\,0,\,1\,]</m>. Find the volume flow rate
					<m>\iint_S \vv\cdot\vn\,dS</m> through the duct.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Air moves straight up a circular ventilation duct with
					velocity <m>\vv = [\,0,\,0,\,3\,]</m> m/s. Model the duct's
					cross-section as the flat disk <m>S</m> of radius <m>2</m> m
					in a horizontal plane, with upward unit normal
					<m>\vn = [\,0,\,0,\,1\,]</m>. Find the volume flow rate
					<m>\iint_S \vv\cdot\vn\,dS</m> through the duct.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					On the disk <m>\vv\cdot\vn = [\,0,\,0,\,3\,]\cdot[\,0,\,0,\,1\,] = 3</m>,
					a constant, so the flux is just that constant times the
					area of the disk:
					<md>
						\iint_S \vv\cdot\vn\,dS = 3\cdot\big(\pi (2)^2\big)
						= 12\pi \approx 37.7 \text{ m}^3/\text{s} .
					</md>
					About <m>37.7</m> cubic meters of air pass up through the
					duct each second <ndash/> a flux integral is exactly how an
					engineer sizes a fan or vent.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<p>
				<alert>Looking ahead.</alert> With surfaces parametrized and
				flux in hand, the course closes with the two theorems that
				generalize Green's: <term>Stokes' Theorem</term> equates the
				circulation of a field around the boundary curve of a surface
				with the flux of its <em>curl</em> through the surface, and the
				<term>Divergence Theorem</term> equates the flux of a field out
				of a closed surface with the integral of its
				<em>divergence</em> over the solid inside. Both turn the
				surface integrals of this worksheet into the capstones of
				vector analysis.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>

</worksheet>
